01:31:15.840 --> 01:31:18.960
I'd like to ask about some
ethical aspect of the Genesis

01:31:18.960 --> 01:31:19.460
story.

01:31:19.460 --> 01:31:23.370
So, as I know, Adam
and Eve suddenly

01:31:23.370 --> 01:31:26.990
recognized their shame
when they're being nude

01:31:26.990 --> 01:31:30.860
after eating the apple.

01:31:30.860 --> 01:31:35.690
So I'm wondering, is there
such a shame on nudity?

01:31:35.690 --> 01:31:38.430
Being nude, is it
common in all people,

01:31:38.430 --> 01:31:42.060
including primitive times?

01:31:42.060 --> 01:31:48.120
And if so, is there such a
story about feeling shame

01:31:48.120 --> 01:31:51.341
on nudity in other myths
or other [INAUDIBLE]..

01:31:51.341 --> 01:31:51.840
Yes.

01:31:51.840 --> 01:31:54.220
Yes, I think this
is also a question

01:31:54.220 --> 01:31:56.080
that Stephen and
Richard could speak to,

01:31:56.080 --> 01:31:59.140
but part of what
was so upsetting

01:31:59.140 --> 01:32:03.730
to Europeans in the early
modern era, and even to Darwin

01:32:03.730 --> 01:32:06.160
when he visited
South America, was

01:32:06.160 --> 01:32:09.220
that he saw people with really
different conceptions of shame

01:32:09.220 --> 01:32:09.880
from his own.

01:32:09.880 --> 01:32:12.310
He saw people who went
about pretty much naked.

01:32:12.310 --> 01:32:16.420
So that form of shame was
not, in fact, universal.

01:32:16.420 --> 01:32:17.300
Right.

01:32:17.300 --> 01:32:17.800
Yes.

01:32:17.800 --> 01:32:21.882
So is there a people feeling
no shame totally nude,

01:32:21.882 --> 01:32:27.860
or they have some
minimal [INAUDIBLE] on?

01:32:27.860 --> 01:32:29.360
Yeah, there are.

01:32:29.360 --> 01:32:31.641
Well, yes.

01:32:31.641 --> 01:32:32.140
I think so.

01:32:32.140 --> 01:32:33.840
I'm pretty darn sure.

01:32:33.840 --> 01:32:38.260
I'm racking my brain
for photographs.

01:32:38.260 --> 01:32:42.070
It reminds me-- this
issue-- of Chagnon's story

01:32:42.070 --> 01:32:47.950
about the Yanomami
in Venezuela where

01:32:47.950 --> 01:32:53.790
the men wear a string that is
tied to the top of the penis,

01:32:53.790 --> 01:32:58.060
and it holds the penis
up near to their waist.

01:32:58.060 --> 01:33:01.200
And a man would not be seen
dead without his penis string.

01:33:01.200 --> 01:33:03.710
But it covers nothing.

01:33:03.710 --> 01:33:06.780
It's totally symbolic.

01:33:06.780 --> 01:33:09.880
And so what happens is
with missionary histories,

01:33:09.880 --> 01:33:11.710
particular Christian
missionary histories,

01:33:11.710 --> 01:33:17.150
is that ideas of shame
that are drawn from Genesis

01:33:17.150 --> 01:33:20.500
are then imposed on
other peoples who have,

01:33:20.500 --> 01:33:24.840
as Richard said, very, very
different cultural notions

01:33:24.840 --> 01:33:26.740
of dress, of shame,
very different.

01:33:26.740 --> 01:33:30.880
And it becomes extremely
difficult to understand those

01:33:30.880 --> 01:33:33.480
because they're coming
out of the story.

01:33:33.480 --> 01:33:35.020
I mean, it's possible.

01:33:35.020 --> 01:33:39.200
There's other questions, so
let's pass the microphone

01:33:39.200 --> 01:33:39.700
around.

01:33:42.320 --> 01:33:46.755
I almost hate to bring this
up, but the story of Lilith.

01:33:46.755 --> 01:33:49.645
Did you pay any attention
to that in your book?

01:33:49.645 --> 01:33:51.055
That is so far afield.

01:33:54.589 --> 01:33:57.130
I mean, I mentioned Lilith and
discussed her briefly, but not

01:33:57.130 --> 01:33:57.790
a lot of time.

01:33:57.790 --> 01:34:03.250
But I think it's a fantastically
interesting story, precisely

01:34:03.250 --> 01:34:10.320
because it takes to
a more extreme point

01:34:10.320 --> 01:34:13.940
the question of dominance
and disobedience.

01:34:13.940 --> 01:34:20.820
The Lilith stories, I'm sure
you know, it's not biblical,

01:34:20.820 --> 01:34:24.911
but about a possible, and there
are many speculations about

01:34:24.911 --> 01:34:26.410
this-- and rabbinical
speculations--

01:34:26.410 --> 01:34:30.310
about possible alternative or
earlier attempts on God's part

01:34:30.310 --> 01:34:32.320
to do something--

01:34:32.320 --> 01:34:38.410
in this case, an
extra-rabbinical a possible

01:34:38.410 --> 01:34:43.420
creation of a female who refused
to obey, and in this case

01:34:43.420 --> 01:34:44.420
gave up.

01:34:44.420 --> 01:34:46.450
I mean, was threatened
with dire punishments,

01:34:46.450 --> 01:34:49.270
including the killing
of her offspring

01:34:49.270 --> 01:34:51.220
and nonetheless
refused because she

01:34:51.220 --> 01:34:58.300
said she was made of the same
or better stuff from Adam.

01:34:58.300 --> 01:35:01.720
The reason I don't
talk about it,

01:35:01.720 --> 01:35:04.120
not simply out of
ignorance, but partly

01:35:04.120 --> 01:35:07.670
because what fascinated me
is that the biblical story

01:35:07.670 --> 01:35:11.800
already, even though it has
this enormously long history

01:35:11.800 --> 01:35:16.060
of misogyny associated with it,
has the counter-argument also

01:35:16.060 --> 01:35:20.170
built into it, that what
surfaces in the Lilith story

01:35:20.170 --> 01:35:24.460
is already what looks
like a much more orthodox

01:35:24.460 --> 01:35:26.410
and conventional story of Eve.

01:35:26.410 --> 01:35:34.480
There are many people who say
from very early on that Eve

01:35:34.480 --> 01:35:38.350
is the hero of the story, that
the disobedience is correct,

01:35:38.350 --> 01:35:41.090
that Eve is superior to
Adam because she was created

01:35:41.090 --> 01:35:43.480
by the flesh and not
dirt, and because she

01:35:43.480 --> 01:35:46.400
was created in the garden
and not out of the garden.

01:35:46.400 --> 01:35:49.810
And that is to say, one of the
strange, fascinating things

01:35:49.810 --> 01:35:52.590
about the story-- and
it goes back to issues

01:35:52.590 --> 01:35:58.594
that Kimberley also
raised-- is that I

01:35:58.594 --> 01:36:00.760
don't think it's a mark of
a difference between myth

01:36:00.760 --> 01:36:01.610
and literature.

01:36:01.610 --> 01:36:03.370
But I think it is
the mark of what

01:36:03.370 --> 01:36:05.470
is interesting in both
myth and literature, which

01:36:05.470 --> 01:36:08.680
is the possibility of an
alternative interpretation

01:36:08.680 --> 01:36:12.080
built into what looks
like a closed system.

01:36:12.080 --> 01:36:14.890
And the Adam and Eve
story is astonishing to me

01:36:14.890 --> 01:36:20.750
because in a tiny compass,
50 or 75 verses, you have--

01:36:20.750 --> 01:36:22.310
Alternative interpretations.

01:36:22.310 --> 01:36:25.210
Violently alternative
interpretations

01:36:25.210 --> 01:36:28.960
that are hidden inside,
including Lilith, strangely

01:36:28.960 --> 01:36:31.390
enough, built into
a story that looks

01:36:31.390 --> 01:36:33.150
like it's a clue excluding her.

01:36:36.531 --> 01:36:37.980
Yeah, please.

01:36:37.980 --> 01:36:40.930
I have a question
about language.

01:36:40.930 --> 01:36:42.740
You brought up language.

01:36:42.740 --> 01:36:45.120
And in the passage
that you mentioned

01:36:45.120 --> 01:36:49.860
when Eve actually gets the
apple, she desires the apple,

01:36:49.860 --> 01:36:53.370
she desires to know
and to know beauty.

01:36:53.370 --> 01:36:56.880
We imagine that this
happens through language.

01:36:56.880 --> 01:37:01.620
And yet, in the later
iterations of the story,

01:37:01.620 --> 01:37:04.120
there was a huge question
in the Middle Ages

01:37:04.120 --> 01:37:07.530
and in the early modern
period whether the first word

01:37:07.530 --> 01:37:10.920
was actually uttered
in paradise or outside.

01:37:10.920 --> 01:37:13.680
And Dante actually
leaves it open.

01:37:13.680 --> 01:37:16.110
He says in the De
vulgari, he says

01:37:16.110 --> 01:37:19.740
the first word was uttered
either inside or outside

01:37:19.740 --> 01:37:20.440
the paradise.

01:37:20.440 --> 01:37:24.570
So it's a very interesting,
complicated question

01:37:24.570 --> 01:37:27.780
about the relationship
between language and knowledge

01:37:27.780 --> 01:37:31.260
and beauty and aesthetics
and desire, perhaps, also.

01:37:31.260 --> 01:37:33.670
And I wonder whether
you could speak to that?

01:37:36.180 --> 01:37:40.500
I mean, there is, as
you know, as well as I,

01:37:40.500 --> 01:37:45.950
there's an enormous history
of painting in which there

01:37:45.950 --> 01:37:50.410
are gestures, in
which all of this

01:37:50.410 --> 01:37:53.350
is acted out without
language at all,

01:37:53.350 --> 01:37:57.900
but with bafflement,
head scratching,

01:37:57.900 --> 01:38:01.620
or sexual temptation,
the variety of things

01:38:01.620 --> 01:38:05.340
that don't necessarily
involve language at all.

01:38:05.340 --> 01:38:08.220
It is the case that the
tradition that thinks

01:38:08.220 --> 01:38:09.690
that the words existed already.

01:38:09.690 --> 01:38:10.350
In

01:38:10.350 --> 01:38:12.660
There are interpretations
of the story that

01:38:12.660 --> 01:38:14.910
imagine that not
only did, of course,

01:38:14.910 --> 01:38:16.830
as Adam gives the
names to the animals

01:38:16.830 --> 01:38:19.140
and imagines it as
linguistic-giving,

01:38:19.140 --> 01:38:21.780
but also imagines that
Adam had written already

01:38:21.780 --> 01:38:24.840
a great philosophical
encyclopedia

01:38:24.840 --> 01:38:28.380
about the world, because one
strong line of interpretation

01:38:28.380 --> 01:38:31.140
is that humans lost knowledge.

01:38:31.140 --> 01:38:32.850
Humans once possessed
more knowledge

01:38:32.850 --> 01:38:34.560
and lost it then,
so that Adam must

01:38:34.560 --> 01:38:37.350
have had a much fuller
linguistic capacity.

01:38:37.350 --> 01:38:39.540
And that this goes
against precisely

01:38:39.540 --> 01:38:42.330
the alternative theory.

01:38:42.330 --> 01:38:47.250
I don't know enough about the
innumerable alternative origin

01:38:47.250 --> 01:38:50.370
stories to know if the
issue of language comes up.

01:38:50.370 --> 01:38:53.620
It does in interesting ways.

01:38:53.620 --> 01:38:56.910
And one thing, just to
note, is that the Jewish

01:38:56.910 --> 01:39:00.420
and the Christian and the
Islamic cosmogonic story

01:39:00.420 --> 01:39:03.830
is not the only one
where the gods create

01:39:03.830 --> 01:39:05.340
the Earth through language.

01:39:05.340 --> 01:39:10.440
And so Genesis is very
startling in that way--

01:39:10.440 --> 01:39:18.200
God says, he says the world into
being, he speaks it into being.

01:39:18.200 --> 01:39:20.640
And this is the case in
the Popol Vuh, as well,

01:39:20.640 --> 01:39:24.000
the Mayan creation cosmogony.

01:39:24.000 --> 01:39:27.074
So of course that's picked up--

01:39:27.074 --> 01:39:29.490
and I think you mentioned
this-- with the Christian notion

01:39:29.490 --> 01:39:32.029
of the logos, the
words that creates

01:39:32.029 --> 01:39:33.070
at the beginning of time.

01:39:33.070 --> 01:39:34.680
So we even see these
interesting icons

01:39:34.680 --> 01:39:39.330
where you find Jesus Christ
walking in the Garden of Eden

01:39:39.330 --> 01:39:41.310
as the Logos, as God.

01:39:41.310 --> 01:39:44.010
I mean, that's a very common
icon in the orthodox tradition,

01:39:44.010 --> 01:39:46.050
as well.

01:39:46.050 --> 01:39:50.670
But yeah, the role of
language is not uniformly

01:39:50.670 --> 01:39:54.570
stressed, or even mentioned
in some cosmogonies.

01:39:54.570 --> 01:39:57.690
My point is it's not
seen in all cosmogonies

01:39:57.690 --> 01:40:04.080
as the primary crowning
achievement of creation

01:40:04.080 --> 01:40:05.760
or of human life.

01:40:05.760 --> 01:40:09.282
It's really interesting to
work in a preliterate dig

01:40:09.282 --> 01:40:10.740
where there was no
written history,

01:40:10.740 --> 01:40:12.420
but there had to
have been language.

01:40:12.420 --> 01:40:16.920
And to know that histories
were being told and shared,

01:40:16.920 --> 01:40:20.130
and yet not in a way
that we could have access

01:40:20.130 --> 01:40:22.050
to through written
records, but had

01:40:22.050 --> 01:40:26.040
to begin to infer through other
forms of symbolic thought,

01:40:26.040 --> 01:40:29.010
like hand paintings and
architectural arrangements

01:40:29.010 --> 01:40:32.040
and the use of wild animal parts
inside houses, and burials,

01:40:32.040 --> 01:40:32.970
and so forth.

01:40:32.970 --> 01:40:41.790
Is it believed, Richard, now
that chimpanzees possess some--

01:40:41.790 --> 01:40:42.600
Language?

01:40:42.600 --> 01:40:45.330
Something that approaches or--

01:40:45.330 --> 01:40:46.770
No.

01:40:46.770 --> 01:40:50.280
What chimpanzees do is a
relatively sophisticated form

01:40:50.280 --> 01:40:52.080
of animal communication,
but it doesn't

01:40:52.080 --> 01:40:56.730
have anything like the
symbolic strength of humans.

01:40:56.730 --> 01:41:05.445
So you can bring chimpanzees
up to use hand signs,

01:41:05.445 --> 01:41:09.390
and they could end up
using maybe a few hundred.

01:41:09.390 --> 01:41:14.550
They can combine them into
two or three word chunks.

01:41:14.550 --> 01:41:16.230
A tweet, in effect.

01:41:16.230 --> 01:41:17.350
Sorry?

01:41:17.350 --> 01:41:21.670
Yeah, exactly, yes,
yes, the original tweet.

01:41:21.670 --> 01:41:24.960
But it's still
enormously simple.

01:41:24.960 --> 01:41:29.710
And so if we're
talking about language,

01:41:29.710 --> 01:41:32.860
I think that there is a very
strong case that only Homo

01:41:32.860 --> 01:41:34.620
sapiens has had language.

01:41:34.620 --> 01:41:38.840
The Neanderthals, for all
of their cultural creativity

01:41:38.840 --> 01:41:41.240
in a number of
ways, and they were

01:41:41.240 --> 01:41:45.970
able to do almost everything
that Homo sapiens did,

01:41:45.970 --> 01:41:49.070
but they did it at
incredibly low rates.

01:41:49.070 --> 01:41:52.940
And a predominant
interpretation is

01:41:52.940 --> 01:41:54.890
that the big difference
between sapiens

01:41:54.890 --> 01:42:01.152
and our Neanderthal companions
was that they had no language.

01:42:01.152 --> 01:42:04.751
It's special to us.

01:42:04.751 --> 01:42:05.250
Yes?

01:42:05.250 --> 01:42:06.150
I'm over here.

01:42:06.150 --> 01:42:09.270
I want to first thank you
for a fascinating discussion.

01:42:09.270 --> 01:42:11.010
I wanted to turn
to the part of it

01:42:11.010 --> 01:42:15.030
where you were all commenting
on the time period from Darwin

01:42:15.030 --> 01:42:19.440
after, where there is this
sense of maybe disappointment

01:42:19.440 --> 01:42:24.910
or loss or difficulty in
reconciling views of the past

01:42:24.910 --> 01:42:27.270
that have a god in them,
and views of the past that

01:42:27.270 --> 01:42:29.230
have science in them.

01:42:29.230 --> 01:42:32.550
And if you think of
two groups of people

01:42:32.550 --> 01:42:36.360
moving along different
tracks and thinking

01:42:36.360 --> 01:42:39.360
about the tension
between those groups

01:42:39.360 --> 01:42:42.630
that we sometimes see
the results of now.

01:42:42.630 --> 01:42:44.040
But that doesn't
necessarily have

01:42:44.040 --> 01:42:49.260
to be so because there is an
interpolation about our origin,

01:42:49.260 --> 01:42:52.770
but that can co-exist,
right, that difference

01:42:52.770 --> 01:42:53.670
an interpolation.

01:42:53.670 --> 01:42:57.810
It's where differences
in extrapolation

01:42:57.810 --> 01:43:01.710
about what our
origin implies, that

01:43:01.710 --> 01:43:05.880
seems to be the cause
of more of the tension.

01:43:05.880 --> 01:43:08.250
So I'm wondering if
any or all of you

01:43:08.250 --> 01:43:12.900
have thought about whether it's
necessary that interpolating

01:43:12.900 --> 01:43:15.810
back leads to the results
of extrapolating forward

01:43:15.810 --> 01:43:20.190
that appear to diverge and
creates such problems for us.

01:43:20.857 --> 01:43:22.440
That's such a great
way of putting it.

01:43:22.440 --> 01:43:25.440
Could you say more about the
issue of what it implies?

01:43:25.440 --> 01:43:27.570
How do you see it?

01:43:27.570 --> 01:43:34.260
Well, one tends to think about
these days about legislation

01:43:34.260 --> 01:43:38.820
that seems to reflect
strong religious beliefs.

01:43:38.820 --> 01:43:42.060
And those religious beliefs
correlate with strong views

01:43:42.060 --> 01:43:43.560
about literalism.

01:43:43.560 --> 01:43:50.900
In terms of interpretation
of religious texts.

01:43:50.900 --> 01:43:56.610
And so to me, the tension
of the two streams

01:43:56.610 --> 01:44:01.710
plays out in a vision
of society that,

01:44:01.710 --> 01:44:05.220
at least on the edges of
those things, seems to differ

01:44:05.220 --> 01:44:08.220
Yeah, I mean, I don't mean to
split hairs, but I would say,

01:44:08.220 --> 01:44:11.430
perhaps a certain
strand of interpretation

01:44:11.430 --> 01:44:12.850
of religious texts.

01:44:12.850 --> 01:44:14.670
For example, the
Quran says, if God

01:44:14.670 --> 01:44:19.810
had wanted to make just one
religion, he would have.

01:44:19.810 --> 01:44:25.320
And there are many other strands
within religious traditions

01:44:25.320 --> 01:44:25.980
that are--

01:44:28.889 --> 01:44:31.180
I don't want to use the word
tolerant because it sounds

01:44:31.180 --> 01:44:32.971
like poison and I wish
we'd get rid of it--

01:44:32.971 --> 01:44:36.040
but that are
egalitarian, for example,

01:44:36.040 --> 01:44:43.210
or not seeking to discriminate,
to divide, to elevate,

01:44:43.210 --> 01:44:45.460
to be hierarchical,
but the opposite.

01:44:45.460 --> 01:44:47.279
So I just wanted
to make that point

01:44:47.279 --> 01:44:49.195
that we're talking about
interpretive strands.

01:44:49.195 --> 01:44:50.980
Right, and I didn't
mean to imply tolerance.

01:44:50.980 --> 01:44:51.640
No, no, I know you didn't.

01:44:51.640 --> 01:44:52.556
No, I know you didn't.

01:44:52.556 --> 01:44:57.610
It's just the sense of, can't
we get people into a room

01:44:57.610 --> 01:45:01.480
and try and all get along.

01:45:01.480 --> 01:45:03.910
But we don't have to
interpolate the same way.

01:45:03.910 --> 01:45:06.620
We can coexist believing
very different things.

01:45:06.620 --> 01:45:07.430
Apparently not.

01:45:07.430 --> 01:45:08.020
Extrapolation.

01:45:08.020 --> 01:45:09.170
But not, though.

01:45:09.170 --> 01:45:10.130
But so not.

01:45:10.130 --> 01:45:12.380
What is happening?

01:45:12.380 --> 01:45:14.370
And I love your question.

01:45:14.370 --> 01:45:17.680
And a part of me wonders, you
refer to the time after Darwin.

01:45:17.680 --> 01:45:20.950
And even while Darwin himself
was very retiring and really

01:45:20.950 --> 01:45:25.300
reticent about this, some of
the proponents of his theory

01:45:25.300 --> 01:45:29.770
actually staged conflict The
really famous conversation

01:45:29.770 --> 01:45:33.610
between Thomas Huxley and Bishop
Samuel Wilberforce at Oxford

01:45:33.610 --> 01:45:37.090
at the British Association
for the Advancement of Science

01:45:37.090 --> 01:45:39.940
meeting, which is the one where
Wilberforce said something

01:45:39.940 --> 01:45:43.660
like, on which side are you
descended from a monkey.

01:45:43.660 --> 01:45:45.520
The whole monkey-human
business was nowhere

01:45:45.520 --> 01:45:47.394
in Darwin's writing,
but this was a great way

01:45:47.394 --> 01:45:48.800
to publicize these issues.

01:45:48.800 --> 01:45:49.300
Right.

01:45:49.300 --> 01:45:51.490
And there was a group of
progressive theologians

01:45:51.490 --> 01:45:53.260
in the Church of
England who published

01:45:53.260 --> 01:45:56.020
a set of essays that accepted
transmutationary kinds

01:45:56.020 --> 01:45:56.920
of theories.

01:45:56.920 --> 01:46:00.820
Other parts of the Church
of England went haywire.

01:46:00.820 --> 01:46:02.810
It depends on your
interpretation.

01:46:02.810 --> 01:46:04.240
So I'm wondering,
and I genuinely

01:46:04.240 --> 01:46:06.850
don't know this, if
that kind of a start,

01:46:06.850 --> 01:46:09.520
if the theory getting off
to that kind of a start

01:46:09.520 --> 01:46:11.680
laid the groundwork
for the conflicts

01:46:11.680 --> 01:46:16.210
that you're describing
in contemporary stakes.

01:46:16.210 --> 01:46:20.320
I mean, again, not to push us
where we can't live together,

01:46:20.320 --> 01:46:27.230
but isn't it the case that you,
Richard, as a primatologist,

01:46:27.230 --> 01:46:31.360
are not, how shall we say,
only happen to be interested

01:46:31.360 --> 01:46:34.900
in a particular animal,
namely chimpanzees,

01:46:34.900 --> 01:46:36.610
that you know a great
deal about, but are

01:46:36.610 --> 01:46:38.740
interested in the
relationship of chimpanzees

01:46:38.740 --> 01:46:39.760
to human origins.

01:46:39.760 --> 01:46:45.070
And the kinds of questions that
you ask about from your study,

01:46:45.070 --> 01:46:52.710
what are the origins of human
violence and warfare, or how

01:46:52.710 --> 01:46:55.920
did humans acquire
the brains that

01:46:55.920 --> 01:46:59.770
enable us to process
the things that we do--

01:46:59.770 --> 01:47:03.130
those questions, I won't
say are religious questions,

01:47:03.130 --> 01:47:09.490
but they're not on
parallel tracks.

01:47:09.490 --> 01:47:11.590
I think it's extremely
difficult to keep there

01:47:11.590 --> 01:47:13.660
from being some
kind of collusion.

01:47:13.660 --> 01:47:16.450
Well, I'm bound to
agree, I must say.

01:47:16.450 --> 01:47:21.850
It came home for me
in practice in 2009,

01:47:21.850 --> 01:47:24.280
which was the 200th
anniversary of Darwin's death.

01:47:24.280 --> 01:47:27.730
And the British Council
held a meeting in Egypt,

01:47:27.730 --> 01:47:31.510
hoping to have some kind
of synthesis of thought

01:47:31.510 --> 01:47:34.360
with Islamic scholars.

01:47:34.360 --> 01:47:40.960
And I would say the email chain
went on for months afterwards

01:47:40.960 --> 01:47:45.250
with anyone from an
Islamic country objecting

01:47:45.250 --> 01:47:47.680
to the notion of
evolutionary theory.

01:47:47.680 --> 01:47:50.610
It was impossible to find
any kind of resolution.

01:47:50.610 --> 01:47:53.800
And I think it's right,
there really is a clash.

01:47:53.800 --> 01:47:59.120
I mean, for me, as a classic,
boring, old materialist,

01:47:59.120 --> 01:48:02.110
I think that what
evolutionary theory has done

01:48:02.110 --> 01:48:06.850
is given us a really wonderful
story of human origins that

01:48:06.850 --> 01:48:12.310
reduces God to a personification
of the interests of the people

01:48:12.310 --> 01:48:14.750
who purvey the story of God.

01:48:14.750 --> 01:48:21.310
And it's a really fascinating
use of myth and story

01:48:21.310 --> 01:48:23.640
in terms of its
social consequences,

01:48:23.640 --> 01:48:27.126
but it's not a
story about origins.

01:48:27.126 --> 01:48:29.500
Richard, I have many Muslim
friends throughout the world.

01:48:29.500 --> 01:48:32.530
I don't know one who doesn't
accept evolutionary theory.

01:48:32.530 --> 01:48:34.390
So perhaps it was
the ones that were

01:48:34.390 --> 01:48:36.940
drawn into that
particular discussion.

01:48:36.940 --> 01:48:38.740
No, I just mean I
think we have to be

01:48:38.740 --> 01:48:43.020
really careful about assuming
that this dichotomy is

01:48:43.020 --> 01:48:43.720
universal.

01:48:43.720 --> 01:48:45.820
I want to ask both
of you, if I could,

01:48:45.820 --> 01:48:47.380
it's something I've
always been dying

01:48:47.380 --> 01:48:50.410
to ask evolutionary biologists.

01:48:50.410 --> 01:48:53.130
If we were, say, beavers,
and we were building

01:48:53.130 --> 01:48:55.780
dams in the shape
of the Taj Mahal

01:48:55.780 --> 01:48:58.180
or the Western
Wall or the Vatican

01:48:58.180 --> 01:49:01.900
or the Pyramids of
Teotihuacan, wouldn't

01:49:01.900 --> 01:49:05.070
evolutionary biologists
be interested in those?

01:49:05.070 --> 01:49:07.750
But because of human
exceptionalism,

01:49:07.750 --> 01:49:10.480
there doesn't seem to
be a really powerful

01:49:10.480 --> 01:49:16.660
and robust and multivalent
exploration of religion,

01:49:16.660 --> 01:49:19.360
religious structures,
as part of evolution.

01:49:19.360 --> 01:49:23.440
Since we agree we're animals,
we're evolved primates,

01:49:23.440 --> 01:49:27.010
we're interested in wasp
nests and beaver dams,

01:49:27.010 --> 01:49:29.320
but we are not
interested in religion

01:49:29.320 --> 01:49:33.130
as an evolutionary entity,
other than the more basic,

01:49:33.130 --> 01:49:36.250
simplistic theories that say,
oh, it's a coping mechanism,

01:49:36.250 --> 01:49:38.380
or it's say a form
of social cohesion.

01:49:38.380 --> 01:49:40.300
I always want to say, say more.

01:49:40.300 --> 01:49:42.380
What else can you say about it?

01:49:42.380 --> 01:49:44.110
I'm not trying to put you on the
spot, but I'm just wondering.

01:49:44.110 --> 01:49:45.850
You introduce me to
your Islamic scholars.

01:49:45.850 --> 01:49:47.850
I'll introduce you to all
the religious scholars

01:49:47.850 --> 01:49:50.230
in evolution.

01:49:50.230 --> 01:49:51.350
It's a big area.

01:49:51.350 --> 01:49:53.710
There's tremendous
excitement about exploring

01:49:53.710 --> 01:49:57.820
all sorts of ideas about the
multiple functions of religion.

01:49:57.820 --> 01:49:59.940
Within an evolutionary
framework,

01:49:59.940 --> 01:50:00.831
since we're primates.

01:50:00.831 --> 01:50:01.330
Absolutely.

01:50:01.330 --> 01:50:02.530
OK, that would be great.

01:50:02.530 --> 01:50:05.410
Because I don't hear that,
I hear them carefully

01:50:05.410 --> 01:50:08.830
patrolled and
separated and, yeah,

01:50:08.830 --> 01:50:12.910
human exceptionalism becomes
exhausting, in a way.

01:50:12.910 --> 01:50:13.730
Oh, well, sorry.

01:50:13.730 --> 01:50:17.170
It is restricted to
an analysis of human.

01:50:17.170 --> 01:50:19.340
Yes, yes, yes.

01:50:19.340 --> 01:50:19.870
But I mean--

01:50:19.870 --> 01:50:22.090
Because primates don't do it.

01:50:22.090 --> 01:50:24.840
Well, I think Jane
Goodall might disagree.

01:50:24.840 --> 01:50:25.980
No, I don't think so.

01:50:25.980 --> 01:50:28.097
OK, well, I've
interviewed her on it.

01:50:28.097 --> 01:50:29.430
But that's OK, we'll talk later.

01:50:29.430 --> 01:50:30.846
I know what you're
thinking about.

01:50:30.846 --> 01:50:31.430
No, I'm not.

01:50:31.430 --> 01:50:33.220
We'll talk later.

01:50:33.220 --> 01:50:40.410
Because chimpanzees throw rocks
under waterfalls and people

01:50:40.410 --> 01:50:44.380
have said, maybe these
waterfall displays

01:50:44.380 --> 01:50:47.770
are worshipping
nature in some way.

01:50:47.770 --> 01:50:50.320
She said that, so let's
stick to the Taj Mahal.

01:50:50.320 --> 01:50:53.590
So you're saying that
those monuments and forms

01:50:53.590 --> 01:50:55.450
of religious thought,
et cetera, are

01:50:55.450 --> 01:50:58.000
being thought about
evolutionarily, as far as what

01:50:58.000 --> 01:51:00.851
they do for us, for example.

01:51:00.851 --> 01:51:01.350
Yes.

01:51:01.350 --> 01:51:03.250
OK, that's great.

01:51:03.250 --> 01:51:06.490
I think on this note of
simultaneous disagreement

01:51:06.490 --> 01:51:11.830
and concord might be
an appropriate time

01:51:11.830 --> 01:51:16.010
to thank you all, and
thank my fellow panelists.

01:51:16.010 --> 01:51:20.560
